The problem you are facing is caused by the placement of the #[link] attribute in your Rust code. The #[link] attribute should be placed just before the extern block, but you have placed a use statement in between. This causes the #[link] attribute to become attached to the use statement instead, rendering it ineffective. Unfortunately, there is no warning for this issue.

To resolve this problem, you need to move the #[link] attribute to the correct position. Here's the corrected code:

```rust
extern "C" {
    #[link(name = "hello")]
    fn greet();
}

fn main() {
    unsafe {
        greet();
    }
}
```

By moving the #[link] attribute directly before the extern block, you ensure that it properly links to the "hello" shared object file. This should resolve the linker error you were experiencing.

Remember to also import the libc crate using the correct syntax:

```rust
use libc::c_char;
```

With this updated code, you should be able to successfully compile your Rust program while importing libc and using your C shared object file.
